.TH DOTENV 1 "2025-06-19" "scriptorium" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
dotenv \- load environment variables from .env files and execute command
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dotenv
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.RB [ \-x | \-\-exec ]
.RB [ \-s | \-\-strict ]
.RB [ \-q | \-\-silent ]
.RB [ \-e
.IR file ]...
.I command
.RI [ args... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dotenv
loads environment variables from one or more .env files and executes a command with the loaded environment. It supports multiline values, quoted strings, and comments.

Environment variables that are already set in the calling environment take precedence over variables defined in .env files. This allows for easy overriding of .env file values.

The .env file format follows common conventions. For detailed syntax information, see
.BR dotenv (5).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-e " " \fIfile\fR
Specify .env file to load. Can be specified multiple times to load multiple files. If not specified, defaults to
.IR .env .
Files are processed in order, with later files overriding variables from earlier files.
.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-exec
Replace the current shell process with the executed command instead of running it in a subprocess.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-strict
Fail with exit code 1 when warnings occur (e.g., missing .env files, unclosed quotes).
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-silent
Suppress warning messages. Does not affect error behavior.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help message and exit.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I command
Command to execute with the loaded environment variables.
.TP
.I args...
Arguments to pass to the command.
.SH VARIABLE PRECEDENCE
Variables are resolved in the following order (highest to lowest precedence):
.RS
.IP 1. 4
Environment variables set in the calling shell
.IP 2. 4
Variables from .env files (processed in command-line order)
.RE

This means that
.B TEST=override dotenv -e .env command
will use "override" as the value of TEST, regardless of what .env contains.

When multiple .env files are specified, later files override variables from earlier files, but only if those variables are not already set in the environment.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
dotenv go run main.go
Execute go command with environment from .env file.
.TP
dotenv -e .env -e .env.production python app.py
Load variables from multiple .env files and run Python script.
.TP
dotenv -e .env.local npm start
Use custom .env file with npm.
.TP
TEST=override dotenv -e .env printenv TEST
Override .env file value with environment variable.
.TP
dotenv -s -e .env.production python app.py
Fail if .env.production is missing instead of just warning.
.TP
dotenv -q -e missing.env node server.js
Suppress warning message about missing.env file.
.TP
dotenv -x -e .env bash
Replace current shell with bash using environment from .env file.
.TP
dotenv --exec node server.js
Replace current process with Node.js server using default .env file.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Success
.TP
1
Error (file not found, parse error, missing command, etc.)
.SH FILES
.TP
.I .env
Default environment file if no -e option is specified.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR dotenv (5),
.BR env (1),
.BR export (1),
.BR source (1),
.BR exec (1)
